Building reliable, high-performing AI systems requires more than prompt engineering — it demands the kind of rigorous observability and systems thinking I've applied across 24 years of engineering, most recently leading AWS/Kubernetes migration performance testing for the USDA.

The AI Automation Engineer role aligns directly with where my skills are headed. While completing my IBM Generative AI Engineering certification and AI Engineer Bootcamp, I've been hands-on with LLMs and cloud-based automation — exactly what this role demands. At USDA, I integrated AppDynamics, Splunk, Prometheus, and Grafana to drive a 40% throughput increase and 35% reduction in defect resolution time. At Sprint/CenturyLink, I scaled systems to 12,000+ transactions per minute — the kind of production-scale pressure that makes AI inference pipelines perform under load.

My AWS experience, combined with active LLM training and a performance engineer's instinct for latency, SLA compliance, and system bottlenecks, gives me a foundation most AI automation candidates simply don't have.

I'm available immediately, fully remote-ready, and would welcome a conversation about contributing to your team.

— Hans Richardson
